The `Input.GetAxis()` function is a method provided by Unity to access the values of virtual axes in your game. This can be used for input handling, such as player movement or camera rotation.

Here is an example of how you can use `Input.GetAxis()` in Unity:

```csharp
public class PlayerController : MonoBehaviour
{
    public float speed = 5f;

    void Update()
    {
        // Get the horizontal input axis
        float horizontalInput = Input.GetAxis("Horizontal");

        // Get the vertical input axis
        float verticalInput = Input.GetAxis("Vertical");

        // Move the player based on the input
        Vector3 movement = new Vector3(horizontalInput, 0f, verticalInput) * speed * Time.deltaTime;
        transform.Translate(movement);
    }
}
```

In this example, we are accessing the horizontal and vertical input axes using `Input.GetAxis("Horizontal")` and `Input.GetAxis("Vertical")` respectively. These axes can be set up in the Unity Input Manager, allowing you to map them to different input devices or keys.

The `Input.GetAxis()` function returns a float value between -1 and 1, depending on the input. A value of -1 represents full negative input, 0 represents no input, and 1 represents full positive input.

By multiplying the input values by `speed` and `Time.deltaTime`, you can control the speed at which the player moves. The `Translate` function then moves the player based on the input.

Remember to attach this script to a GameObject in your scene for it to work properly.

